model.name: CCS Architecture
model.documentation:
When in doubt, the definitions should align with (in this order):
* https://standard.open-contracting.org/latest/en/ * http://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html * https://schema.org/

element.name: Search
element.documentation:
The search is the automatic support to find something.
This is quite broad and probably deserves some decomposition. For example, it's not the same searching for an agreement that searching for a service or even searching for a supplier.
Also, search users are Customers, Suppliers and CCS employees for different reasons and expected results (and legal constraints).

element.name: Supplier verification
element.documentation:
A supplier must provide proofs that they are suitable CCS providers.
Some proofs will be generic and some specific for Agreement or Lot.
Is Sourcing part of this?

element.name: Competitions management
element.documentation: Past and in-flight procurement processes.

element.name: Fulfillment
element.documentation: CCS does not involve itself with fulfillment. This might change in the future.

element.name: Basket management
element.documentation: This aims to represent the fact that buyers need to manage the things they are aiming to buy from a catalogue-based approach.

element.name: Notifications
element.documentation: Some actions e.g. who is being awarded, require notifications

element.name: Audit trail management
element.documentation:
Any procurement process must provide a means to audit that it was a fair process.
Any decision made along de process that conditions what supplier is able opt for being awarded must be recorded here.
Equally a customer has to be able to obtain these audit trails when in need.
Equally CCS has to be able to manage these audits inasmuch to proof they are a fair intermetiary between the parties.

element.name: Agreement management
element.documentation: Each agreement needs to be managed for as long as it is relevant for CCS. This includes the time when the Agreement is no longer in service but it needs to be kept for auditability purposes, legal, etc.

element.name: Reporting
element.documentation: Levy reporting

element.name: Catalogue management
element.documentation:
Suppliers and CCS employees need to add/remove/edit catalogues and catalogue items.
For example, a supplier may want to change an item they offer and CCS needs to review that the change is allowed and valid.

element.name: User identification
element.documentation: Any user of this system needs to be uniquely identified regardless of their type (customer, supplier, ccs employee, ...) Also organisations and groups within need to be identified and managed.

element.name: Developer
element.documentation: The developer is the person writting software.

element.name: Supplier organisation
element.documentation: The supplier is the legal organization who provides a product or service.

element.name: Supplier
element.documentation: The supplier is the legal person part of a supplier organisation who provides a product or service.

element.name: Customer organisation
element.documentation: The customer is the legal organization who is in demand of a product or service.

element.name: Forwarder
element.documentation:
An intermediary in a fulfilment process.
See also https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-SHIPMENT-CONSIGNMENT

element.name: Category manager
element.documentation: A CCS employee from Category Management.

element.name: Customer
element.documentation: The customer is the person part of an organisation who is in demand of a product or service.

element.name: Procurement specialist
element.documentation:
A CCS procurement specialist.
Typically procurement specialists help customers in the buying process.

element.name: Review
element.documentation: A review for an Item or a Supplier qualifying the product or service received.

property.value: The BaT business requirements are vague on how the review system would work

element.name: Framework Lot
element.documentation: A category within a Commercial Agreement with its own set of rules that further constrain what can be offered by Suppliers.

element.name: Rule
element.documentation: A Commercial Agreement Rule defines a constraint that must be accounted for. E.g. Only services oferring in Scotland can be part of the agreement.

property.value: Although the concept is fairly clear, there is a lack of understanding of its shape and types.

element.name: Basket
element.documentation: A Basket is a set of Catalogue Items selected by the Customer from different Commercial Agreements (and different Suppliers).

property.value: Should this be "Bid" instead of "Bid status"?

element.name: Supplier
element.documentation: The supplier is the legal person or organization who provides a product or service.

element.name: Invoice Item
element.documentation:
An invoice item is a line of an invoice. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.
Note that an Invoice Item is not an Item although it is associated with one.

property.value: Is this the same as "Agreement Contract"?

element.name: Role
element.documentation: An access role. Defines what rights are given to an Account.

element.name: Refund
element.documentation: A repayment of a Transaction.

property.value: It is unclear if this information will be available at all.

element.name: Item instance
element.documentation:
Certain Items may be identified and ordered as individual, unique objects—for example, a specific car rather than a make and model of a car.
See https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-ITEM-INSTANCES

element.name: Brief
element.documentation:
A Brief is the specification put together by the Customer to start a procurement process.
Further Competition requires it, Direct Award is unclear at the moment but could help.

element.name: Buyer
element.documentation: The buyer is the legal person or organization acting on behalf of the customer who buys or purchases the goods or services.

property.value: There is a lot of confusion between Buyer and Customer. Most of the time CCS people use "Buyer" to mean "the person that wants to procure something, which this model calls Customer"

element.name: Search Result
element.documentation: A Search result is a set of Items (products and services) from any available Commercial Agreement.

property.value: Depending on how FaT turns out to be, this will need refining. It is here because at some point we considered search results as able to be saved

element.name: Freight
element.documentation: The part of the Order dealing with how goods will be delivered.

property.value: This depends on how Order is used at CCS and how it will the Order will be modelled.

element.name: ProcurementPlan
element.documentation:
Or just Plan?
See https://standard.open-contracting.org/latest/en/getting_started/releases_and_records/

element.name: Agreement
element.documentation: A Commercial Agreement.

element.name: Invoice
element.documentation: A statement of the money due for goods or services; a bill.

element.name: Levy
element.documentation: The levy percentage associated with a particular transaction between a Customer and a Supplier.

property.value: This concept may be more complex as Suppliers pay in bulk some times. Check with business

element.name: Customer
element.documentation: The customer is the legal person or organization who is in demand of a product or service.

element.name: Organisation
element.documentation: A public sector Organisation.

element.name: User Profile
element.documentation:
A user profile is the infoset the CCS system has about a user.
See also: Account Profile

element.name: Agreement Contract
element.documentation: The contract between CCS and a Supplier under a particular Commercial Agreement.

property.value: Is the right name for the concept?

element.name: Budget
element.documentation:
The budget allocated for a competition.
See https://standard.open-contracting.org/latest/en/schema/reference/#budget

element.name: Taxon
element.documentation: A concept part of a taxonomy used to classify Agreements and Lots.

element.name: Catalogue
element.documentation:
A Catalogue is a set of Catalogue Items provided by a Supplier.
A Supplier may have one or more Catalogues per Agreement.
If a Supplier wishes to provide eg localised or time-limited items, that is represented as a distinct Catalogue.
A Catalogue may expire.
A Catalogue has geographical availability.

property.value: It is unclear how this relates to Framework Lot and to Commercial Agreement

element.name: Transaction
element.documentation: A Transaction paying for an Order.

element.name: Item
element.documentation:
An Item may be a Product or Service.
See https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-ITEMS

property.value: The definition of Item is too vague. Needs refinining.

element.name: Asset
element.documentation: A generic digital asset belonging to an Organisation.

element.name: Proof
element.documentation:
The Proof of how the procurement process was done, what criteria was used to award.
It's purpose is to allow an audit.

property.value: Needs refining and check with business on what kind of proofs do we need (e.g. Further Competition may be different than Direct Award or eAuction)

element.name: User Account
element.documentation:
A user account is the materialisation of the access to the CCS system by a user.
See also: UserProfile

element.name: Call for Tenders
element.documentation: A call for tenders defines a procurement project to buy products or services during a specified period.

element.name: Tender
element.documentation: A document whereby an economic operator (the tenderer) makes a formal offer (the tender) to a contracting authority to execute an order for the supply or purchase of goods, or for the execution of work, according to the terms of a proposed contract.

element.name: Unawarded Notification
element.documentation: A document communicating to a tenderer that the contract has been awarded to different tenderer.

element.name: Awarded Notification
element.documentation: The notification that communicates a contract award to the winner.

element.name: Tender Receipt
element.documentation: A document sent by a contracting party to an economic operator acknowledging receipt of a Tender.

element.name: Contract Award Notice
element.documentation: A document published by a Contracting Party to announce the awarding of a procurement project.

element.name: Request for Quotation
element.documentation: A document used to request a Quotation for goods and services from a seller.

element.name: Quotation
element.documentation:
A document used to quote for the provision of goods and services.
Allows a Buyer to get offline approval before placing an Order.
If the quotation has a "Commitment to Buy", the Seller should hold stock for 30 days, or as per Commercial Agreement rules.
See also https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-QUOTATION

element.name: Order Change
element.documentation: A document used to specify changes to an existing Order

element.name: Order Cancellation
element.documentation: A document used to cancel an entire Order.

element.name: Order Item
element.documentation:
An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.
Note that an Order Item is not an Item although it is associated with one.

element.name: Order Response
element.documentation: A document used to indicate detailed acceptance or rejection of an Order or to make a counter-offer.

element.name: Order
element.documentation: An order is a confirmation of a transaction (a receipt), which can contain multiple line items, each represented by an Offer that has been accepted by the customer.

element.documentation: kjhkj

element.name: Seller
element.documentation: The seller is the legal person or organization acting on behalf of the supplier and who sells goods or services to the buyer.

element.name: Consignor
element.documentation:
Typically a Supplier consigns a shippment and a consigment in a fulfilment process.
See https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-SHIPMENT-CONSIGNMENT

element.name: Buyer
element.documentation: The buyer is the legal person or organization acting on behalf of the customer who buys or purchases the goods or services.

element.name: Consignee
element.documentation:
Typically a Buyer receives a shippment and a consigment in a fulfilment process.
See https://docs.oasis-open.org/ubl/os-UBL-2.1/UBL-2.1.html#S-SHIPMENT-CONSIGNMENT

element.name: Other UI
element.documentation: A placeholder UI to symbolise any UI yet to be defined.

element.name: PaT
element.documentation:
Present a Thing. Composes all the (web) User Interfaces.
Formerly known as Front Door.

element.name: Clarification
element.documentation:
A Clarification request.
A Supplier can request a Clarification to a Brief or EOI done by a Customer.

element.name: Service
element.documentation:
A service offered by a Supplier.
Typically procured via Further Competition or Direct Award, as opposed to Product sold in the Shopping cart.

element.name: Product
element.documentation:
A product offered by a Supplier as part of their Catalogue.
Typically sold in the Shopping cart, as opposed to a Service procured via Further Competition or Direct Award.

A procurement contract always relates to an ITT, but could be specific to a procurement lot.
Could be one of type.... Call Off Open Market Single Tender Action

Also known as an expression of interest. The 'status' of the bid relates to a specific supplier and a specific procurement lot. This might be 'invited', 'not invited', 'submitted', 'not interested' 'declined', 'accepted', and so on. Its possible a procurement (lot) will raise no interest from suppliers at all.

The procurement strategy may split the ITT into multiple lots. If the strategy is to advertise the procurement as a whole, then there will be just a single lot. In this latter case Proc Ops will tend to refer to the ITT directly, but the single lot is still valid.

This relationship will allow hierarchies but does not proscribe a structure. Where organisations are part of groups (e.g. govt dept and its ministry), then one organisation is 'a parent of' the other.

Each procurement case should only ever have a maximum of one ITT. If the tender fails, the case should be abandoned and a new one opened in order to maintain a clean case history. However, this principle is not followed in every case.
